Public procurement of construction services and anti-corruption measures
Joint report by the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel examinations
Introduction and overview
The awarding of services by contracting authorities is of great importance to both the state and the economy.
The task of the state is to use the public funds as economically and economically as possible, as well as to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to be able to guarantee largely unlimited competition across borders, the contracting authorities have to comply with EU requirements when awarding contracts from certain value limits (thresholds).
To this end, the EU member states have to transfer and apply the EU's public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Under the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The awarding of services is also an area at risk of corruption.
Due to the fundamentally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue privileges in the awarding of their contracts.
In January 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits both for the award of construction services across the EU and for the prevention of corruption.
The main focus of the examinations was the application of the EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national regulations, as well as the prevention of corruption in the awarding of construction services in civil engineering, road construction and transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU thresholds have also been included in the considerations with regard to the prevention of corruption.
The audit results of both audit bodies are summarised in the present joint report.
The report will also be addressed to international bodies, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
Examination areas and verified bodies The evaluations of the Federal Court of Auditors on the topics listed are mainly based on cross-sectional examinations carried out in 2011 / 2012 by the building authorities responsible for the road and construction of the federal government in Germany.
In doing so, he examined, for example, the construction of motorways and large-scale construction projects.
In addition, the Federal Court of Auditors drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011, which included construction measures in road, rail, water, construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other areas of construction in the Czech Republic.
The awarding of federal public contracts in Germany is predominantly carried out by the building authorities of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the state building administration is centrally responsible for the distribution of transport infrastructure.
In the construction sector, the contracts are carried out decentrally by those bodies that use state budgets.
In both countries, freelancers will also be involved for parts of the procurement process.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in public procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries have to be taken into account.
Development of public procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national sector are governed by budgetary law and the administrative provisions that are based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national contracts,
Such as the so-called "award books" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail, in accordance with the public procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the award procedure is governed exclusively by the Procurement Act and other legal provisions, which apply both to the area above and below the EU thresholds.
The public procurement law was significantly revised in 2012.
The new rules increased transparency in the use of public funds, increased competition and limited opportunities for corruption in the procurement process.
Guidelines for public procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure are to be applied to EU-wide contracts in particular.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are to be applied to the national types of procurement (public tender, limited tender, voluntary award), which, however, are broadly in line with the above-mentioned EU-wide types of procurement.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (for contracts to be carried out across the EU) and the public tender (for national contracts).
In the open procedure and in the public tender process, any interested company can make an offer.
Another key feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises.
The main purpose of this is to divide an overall construction measure into skilled and partially unemployed people.
The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to take part in the competition.
Both of the above features of German public procurement law are proven tools for achieving economic results.
In Germany, there are more than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also to be applied to construction projects below the EU threshold.
One exception is the simplified procedure, which allows a less stringent procedure to be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law, in line with EU law, provides for contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal regulations in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between the open procedure and the non-open procedure.
There are more than 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which around 1,900 have 20 or more employees.
