Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries for the EU-wide award of construction services and for the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both audit bodies compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of civil engineering and road construction.
In doing so, they essentially found:
The EU directives on the award of construction services by public authorities have been transposed into national law both in the Czech Republic and in Germany (points 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, corruption prevention is also served by the procurement regulations of both countries, which are partly different in terms of their focus and detail (no. 3.2).
In both countries, a key requirement for the procurement documents is that they must contain all the information needed to make an appropriate offer.
The performance descriptions must be neutral and must not be subject to competition restrictions.
In Germany, the procurement documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the subject of the order sufficiently.
In Germany, construction services are to be divided into lots, if possible, in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.
In its examinations, in particular in the field of road construction, the NK found that awarding large-scale services without lots or with very large lots could affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.
Reducing the market potential can lead to significant cost increases and run the risk of price or other agreements.
According to the provisions of both countries, the contracting authorities can, under certain conditions, agree on additional or modified services with the companies already commissioned, which prove to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (no. 4.1).
The respective requirements for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.
According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, the contracting authorities are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure for EU-wide contracts or the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national contracts, applies.
As a result, more companies will be able to make offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes it more difficult for bidders to arrange prices and leads to the most economical results.
In the case of construction projects, whose estimated total order values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities generally awarded construction services throughout Europe.
The correct estimation of the prospective contract value is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
In Germany, cost databases are used for the cost investigations of public buildings, in particular in the construction of buildings,
The construction projects that have been completed are based on the evaluations.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (No. 4.2).
In the case of construction services to be awarded across Europe, preliminary information and announcements are to be published, which should strengthen competition by enabling interested companies to adapt to the planned contracts at an early stage.
The inspected building authorities generally adhered to this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or a lack of controls may have affected competition (point 4.3).
The selection of candidates to take part in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be disclosed beforehand.
In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting authorities in both countries are to switch as often as possible among the companies that are to be called upon when selecting candidates.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are some very detailed guidelines in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations failed to take account of these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of candidates were not always understandable (no. 4.4).
In both countries, in the interests of fair competition, it is necessary to ensure that companies interested in making an offer receive the same information during the tender period.
Contact between these companies and with freelancers involved in the creation of the service description must be prevented as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The audited building authorities in Germany, however, did not comply with these requirements in some cases (no. 4.5).
In opening up the offers, both countries must pay particular attention to the multi-eyes principle and the principle of transparency.
The requirements for the identification, documentation, storage and confidentiality of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.
The examinations in both countries resulted in only a few complaints (no. 4.6).
In both countries, the assessment and evaluation of the offers are determined by guidelines for the organisation of construction and procedures.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
For example, contracting authorities handed over offers for testing to third parties without having to look through the offers beforehand and sufficiently document the abnormalities.
As a result, the offers were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (no. 4.7).
At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies participating in the competition will be informed of the intended assignment before the award of the contract.
This possibility of legal protection also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for the possibility of judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases the contracting authorities did not comply with the prescribed deadlines for the orders or deviated from the bidders' offer in terms of content (no. 4.8).
The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible for the audited building authorities in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in respect of the award notices of certain procedures.
Some of the identified defects also diminished the anti-corruption function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries have largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).
The basics of EU public procurement law and corruption prevention
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unlimited competition within the European Union with free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the award coordination and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the Member States of 8.
The general award principles of the European Union are, in particular, the requirement for competition, the requirement for equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination, as well as the requirement for transparency.
To achieve these goals, the Procurement Coordination Directive sets out specific rules for construction works to be awarded across the EU.
In order to do so, their estimated order amounts must reach or exceed the current amount of 5,000,000 euros.
The rules concern in particular the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, inter alia for the receipt of the offers, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualification of the applicants, and the appeal directive forms the basis for the legal protection of the applicants and bidders.
In the event of possible breaches of public procurement law, affected companies can have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union's directives into national law.
Prevention of corruption
The importance of preventing corruption
In both countries, there is no legal definition of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private gain,
Which is usually prompted by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of global economic output.
In the area of the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of contracting authorities, anti-competitive agreements or unfair behaviour can call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.
In doing so, they will have to review the organisation of their administrations in areas that are particularly vulnerable to corruption, in order to make appropriate safeguards against corruption there.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the susceptibility of decision-making to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works services is generally considered to be a particularly corruption-prone area of work.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery, as well as the acceptance and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on the prevention of corruption 12 in the Federal Administration. According to this, in addition to risk analysis, the following basic principles must be observed: Priority for public tenders and open procedures, multi-eyes principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, award and settlement, accuracy and complete documentation of the award procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the public procurement legislation.
In 2011, for example, the responsible Federal Ministry of Public Works introduced an electronically supported control system in the area of federal highways.
The award data - such as estimated costs and order sums - as well as information on the freelancers involved will be collected across the board and evaluated for abnormalities.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also being prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements for transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, form the most important basis for preventing corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has set out anti-corruption measures in a anti-corruption strategy paper for 2011-2012 and updated them for 2013-2014.
Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national public procurement laws and related administrative provisions.
The main provisions of the new legislation are as follows: Lowering the threshold for smaller contracts, requiring the contracting authority to disclose the contracts beforehand, including naming the reasons for the tender, prohibiting the restriction of the number of bidders in non-open procedures and thus removing the possibility of selecting bidders through locking procedures, introducing the obligation to publish the contract documents and all the annexes, introducing the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Results of the examination of the individual phases of the award procedure
Procurement documents
Procurement documents The procurement documents must contain all the information that the bidders need to make an appropriate offer.
In particular, the procurement documents must make it possible to calculate correctly.
In so doing, bidders must not be given risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The contract documents consist, in particular, of the service description and the terms of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders, as well as the criteria that determine the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law for the procurement documents are addressed in particular to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.
The service description must, in principle, be product-neutral.
For this reason, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.
Avoiding restrictions on competition in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the procurement documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of the offers and for manipulation in the evaluation of them.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Similar or similar regulations In both countries, the EU legal requirements for technical specifications have been transposed into national law.
The services are, in principle, product-neutral without the requirements of the factory.
In the performance descriptions, the individual services must, as a rule, be subdivided in detail into performance units with their respective quantities.
Prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. euros per square metre or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the performance descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include services where it is not clear whether they are needed.
Compensation based on lump sums or on time is to be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on unspecified requirements in the procurement documents.
The service descriptions must enable bidders to make their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The call for tenders will not be made public until the tender documents have been completed.
Divergent rules
There is no obligation to tender for construction services in Losen in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, the public procurement authorities can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are basically to be divided into lots, separated according to the quantity (partial) and / or according to type or subject areas (non-skilled).
The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, to expand the number of potential suppliers and to make it more difficult to arrange prices.
This type of award is generally considered to be the most economical.
In the Czech Republic, assessment criteria must be set out in the award documents for both EU-wide and national procedures.
This should allow applicants to fully and conclusively identify the criteria on which their offers should be assessed.
In Germany, the specification of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only required in EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the assessment criteria must only be set out in an internal administrative award notice.
Procurement documents, which are prepared by commissioned freelancers, may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or consultants in Germany for the building construction and for some road construction authorities.
This is to prevent individual companies from obtaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the client's knowledge of contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send procurement documents or to interpret planning documents for inspection.
The only contact person for the companies is the client.
There is currently no provision for this in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services, which turn out to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (additions), are almost always required for large-scale construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions make it possible, to a certain extent, to award additional contracts to the company that has already been commissioned, without having to carry out a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of the supplementary services must not exceed half of the main order.
In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages, or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to the award of such contracts without a public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the company that has already been commissioned, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is generally not possible under the regulations in Germany.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, it is to be assumed that the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order that has already been awarded.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, small quantities cannot be charged for additional supplementary services.
Key findings of the audit
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral bidding
In individual cases, the performance descriptions included references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.
Some performance descriptions also included product-related specifications - for example, for graffiti protection, joints or noise protection plates - without the need for this.
In some cases, performance requirements were so accurately described that only one product was eligible.
Performance lists subdivided by partial services
In none of the cases examined has the BRH found any violation of the requirement to write out services in a list of services subdivided by partial services.
Completeness of performance descriptions
In the vast majority of cases, the procurement documents were completed before the start of the tenders.
In some cases, the procurement documents had to be corrected during the tender phase, as some positions or deadlines had changed.
In some cases, the performance lists contained positions that did not determine whether they were needed.
A list of services for demolition work even consisted of almost half of such requirements.
Loose and evaluation criteria
In the case of many awards, the prescribed justification was missing as to why the services, which were predominantly advertised for non-skilled persons, were not further divided into partial ones.
There were no complaints when specifying the criteria to be taken into account in the assessment of the offers.
References to freelancers
A small part of the performance descriptions contained references to the involved freelancers.
Some of their names were on the cover sheets or in attached plans or reports.
In one case, the contracting authority even explicitly asked the applicants to contact the architect "on questions of the tender."
In the construction sector in particular, the contracting authorities largely attributed the complaints to the failings of the freelancers responsible for drawing up the service descriptions.
The building services pointed to the lack of capacity in order to be able to adequately control the performance descriptions.
