Technical specifications and product-neutral tenders In the case of public procurement for the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units, a supplier and a specific product brand were specified in the performance description.
The contracting authority did not allow the use of comparable products without justifying it.
In the course of the construction of several university buildings, suppliers and products were also specified in the tender.
Performance descriptions with performance units
In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the contracting authority did not clearly specify the scope and type of services required in the performance descriptions.
As a performance unit, it only indicated the refurbished space of the individual buildings in cubic metres.
Completeness of performance descriptions
During the construction of a motorway bypass, the performance descriptions were changed four times in the period from August to September 2009 as part of a non-open procedure,
Since the scope of services had increased considerably and the technical requirements had changed.
Tender documents for social buildings contained inaccurate location information, insufficient technical preliminary examinations and incomplete design drawings, which required additional services to be commissioned.
When building a large library building, the performance description of the interior did not include any requirements for product quality.
As a result of these missing requirements, some subcontractors installed overpriced and unreasonably high-quality equipment.
Loose and fitness criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of construction measures into partial contracts or the award of partial contracts is not compulsory.
An examination of the three large sections of the construction of a motorway ring showed that if selected parts were awarded separately, savings of up to €31.6 million could have been made at a total cost of €620.3 million.
In the case of six different buildings alone, which were the subject of a single contract, EUR 2.5 million (25%) could have been saved in the event of a separate award.
If the construction of 20 bridges were to be awarded separately, savings of €11.5 million (25%) would have been possible compared to a total allocation.
With regard to the award of construction services in road construction, the central contracting authority laid down very extensive reference requirements as fitness criteria.
In the construction of a part of a motorway, the contracting authority required the bidders, in an open procedure, to prove, among other things, that at least three road construction projects, worth 28 million euros each, had been carried out over the past five years.
In the Czech Republic, a maximum of nine suppliers met these requirements.
The public procurement of another section of a motorway consisted of six separate construction projects, in which the contracting authority had set an annual construction volume of at least €480 million over the last three years as an aptitude criterion for the companies.
Two-thirds of the funds raised for road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (i.e. 2.5 billion euros out of a total of 3.7 billion euros) came from commissions from a total of five companies that carried out the contracts alone or as a joint venture.
In 46 bidding procedures with an order volume of 528 million euros, only two or even one bidder made an offer.
The NK pointed out that a narrowing of the market potential could lead to significant cost increases.
Additional services
In the case of the construction of a motorway bypass, the contracting authority did not apply any of the legal procedures for awarding additional services in two cases, nor did it enter into written contracts for the additional services.
Due to unclear quantity and quality specifications, additional orders were made in the first case of up to 63.7 million euros (net) and in the second case up to 165.4 million euros (net), which increased the respective order volume by 21% and 91% respectively.
