Other findings
On the basis of a sample of construction projects, the NK found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway in the Czech Republic was up to €14.6 million.
In Deuschland, on the other hand, according to an analysis of long-term data from the Federal Ministry of Building, the average cost of a four-lane motorway kilometre is up to 10.4 million euros.
This comparison suggests that motorway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take account of the EU's requirements.
They serve both full and fair competition and the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient accuracy of the performance descriptions should enable bidders to calculate and prepare their offers in an appropriate manner,
Protect the client from additional services to be agreed upon afterwards, and also limit the scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for the procurement documents are supplemented by regulations that are intended to further reduce restrictions on competition and the possibility of manipulation.
In the Czech Republic, there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency will be increased by publishing the evaluation criteria for non-EU procurement procedures.
The requirements for describing performance have largely been met in both countries.
In some cases, however, deviations had to be objected to, which may also have led to restrictions on competition.
The requirement for the formation of lots in Germany promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of the NK, the award of extensive services without lots, or with only very large lots, may result in restrictions on the provider's field to only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements for road construction in the Czech Republic have meant that public contracts are only awarded to a narrow range of suppliers and that small and medium-sized enterprises are not allowed to compete.
In addition, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other agreements.
When awarding and compensating for additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
According to the EU requirements as well as the German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded under certain conditions without public procurement procedures.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies, until additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiation process without notice.
