Determining the type of award and the eligibility of the EU threshold
By determining the type of award, the client determines the number of companies taking part in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential candidates and bidders largely unrestricted, for example by choosing an open procedure, or by setting a limit on non-public procurement procedures.
For construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, Europe-wide procurement procedures are to be applied.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption
When selecting the type of award, the contracting authority must take into account, in particular, the European legal requirements for competition and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of the construction services of a project is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5,000,000 euros, the construction services must in principle be awarded across Europe in accordance with open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
In the case of construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold, the contracting authority may, to a limited extent, deviate from the principle of Europe-wide award and award works in national contracts, provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than €1,000,000 and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total contract value of all construction contracts.
A uniform construction project must not be divided into individual measures without compelling reason, or deliberately valued at too low a cost, in order to avoid the obligation to award construction services on a Europe-wide basis.
As restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of type of award is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification of the type of award chosen, as well as the examination of the obligation to apply the EU procurement rules, are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully implemented EU rules on procurement procedures and the threshold in national law.
Divergent rules
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental equivalence of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU directive to its building contracts, which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open procedure and the non-open procedure, without the decision being doctored or justified, but other procedures are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or - in the case of national tenders - the public call for tenders are, in principle, a priority. This is determined by budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the guidelines for the prevention of corruption.
Other types of procurement - as well as the non-open procedure or the limited invitation to tender - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated by the public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be substantiated and documented.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or the public tender is intended to ensure that competition is as unlimited as possible, to rule out the possibility of manipulation by fixing certain bidders, and to make it more difficult for bidders to agree on prices.
The principle of public tender is a central element of the prevention of corruption in Germany.
The correct estimation of the prospective contract value is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
Construction services in Germany can use the planning and cost databases of public administrations and other organisations to determine the expected costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost indicators for building categories, utilization units, components or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost indicators, it is possible to determine the expected order value of a planned ramp-up or construction performance to be awarded.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction have only a few building authorities in Germany.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road construction authorities is planned.
