In it, he has to make known, among other things, the scope of services, the process and execution dates, the special requirements, as well as the evaluation criteria and their weighting.
The vocabulary of the Common Procurement Vocabulary (CPV codes), which is standardized across Europe, is to be used in the description of the subject of the order.
Preliminary information and notices will be published in the Official Journal of the European Union and in the client's procurement profile.
In order to prevent discrimination against foreign interested parties, notices at the national level may not contain any additional information and may only be issued to the Office for Official Publications of the European Union after the notice has been sent.
Incomplete or inaccurate information in the notice may affect competition and, if necessary, may even support manipulation.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully implemented the EU legal requirements for advance information and notification into national law.
Divergent rules
In the Czech Republic, preliminary information and announcements are also to be published in the case of construction services that are not to be sold across Europe.
Procurement procedures may begin at the earliest one month after the advance information has been sent to the EU Official Journal (for EU-wide contracts) or to the national Official Journal (for all contracts).
It is only in exceptional cases that the publication of a preliminary information can be dispensed with.
In Germany, no advance information is required in the non-EU procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, notices for public tenders and participation competitions must be published on the Federal Government's Internet portal and, if necessary, in newspapers or magazines, before limited tenders.
In the case of limited tenders without competition, notices of services to be awarded from 25,000 euros are required (ex-ante transparency).
All planned lots of the construction projects are to be listed in the preliminary information.
In Germany, this is of particular importance because of the small size of the detached building contracts.
In the Czech Republic, the impact of this scheme is limited, as there are significantly fewer construction services being divided into lots.
