Selection of candidates for non-public contracts
In contrast to public procurement procedures, not every company interested in carrying out the services to be awarded will be able to compete in the non-public procurement procedures.
In the case of non-public procurement procedures, the contracting authority must make a selection beforehand as to which companies should be invited to submit tenders.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption The EU rules allow for a limit on the number of applicants for EU-wide non-public procurement procedures.
However, in the case of non-open procedures, at least five companies are required to submit tenders.
At least three companies are to be invited to take part in the negotiation procedure with the announcement of the contract.
In any case, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not lead to discrimination and must be disclosed beforehand.
The selection of demanding companies is a process within the procurement process that is highly susceptible to manipulation, for example by allowing certain companies to be given one-sided preference.
In addition, restricting competition to a small number of companies also favours possible agreements between candidates.
In both cases, the result can be significantly impaired at the expense of the client.
The contracting authorities must therefore take special precautions against possible manipulation, carry out sufficient checks and, in particular, ensure the transparency and traceability of this step in the process.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
The rules for selecting candidates are similar in both countries.
In addition to the EU requirements, when selecting candidates, the contracting authorities are to switch as often as possible among the companies that are required to do so.
Nor should competition be limited to companies based in certain regions.
The contracting authorities have to justify the selection of the candidates and document the course of the selection process in their award notices.
Divergent rules
In Germany, in the case of limited tenders, at least three candidates are to be invited to submit offers, and in the case of voluntary tenders, several suitable candidates are to be invited to submit offers.
Under the new Czech rules, it is inadmissible - apart from two specific areas - to limit the number of bidders in the event of open procedures and negotiation procedures.
In Germany, the multi-eyes principle is to be observed when selecting companies.
For example, if an employee has proposed a number of companies for a non-public procurement procedure, the management level of the construction service or a commissioner from the contracting authority generally have to amend this proposal by, for example, removing a proposed company and / or supplementing a new company.
The aim is to prevent a single person from being able to definitively determine the circle of companies to be involved in the competition.
Otherwise, in the case of manipulative intentions, this could allow for far-reaching agreements between the parties involved.
The list of companies to be requested is to be treated confidentially - even with regard to freelancers - and not to be made available to the general public.
