Due to the high risk of manipulation in the selection of candidates in non-public procurement procedures, both countries have taken special precautions to prevent undue restrictions on competition.
With the multi-eyes principle, the secrecy of the bidders' lists and the exclusive authority of the contracting authorities to propose the companies to be charged, the German regulations restrict such opportunities for abuse.
In the case of Czech regulations, the newly introduced requirement for the largely unlimited number of bidders in non-public proceedings can, in particular, counteract possible manipulative restrictions.
However, the audit findings have shown that some of these requirements have been poorly implemented and that the potential for manipulation for abusive restriction of the field of participants has not been sufficiently reduced in these cases.
