Opening of offers
Opening of offers
During the opening date, the previously closed offers will be opened and their contents will be read out and made public.
From the opening date, the bidders will be bound by their offers until the deadline set by the contracting authority has expired.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption
There are no separate EU legal provisions for opening the offers.
However, for this highly sensitive phase of the procurement process, the national anti-corruption rules contain extensive requirements to protect bids and competition.
The multi-eyes principle, as well as the transparency and traceability of the opening of the offer, are intended to prevent manipulation and alterations to the submitted offers.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
The opening date is to be carried out by a number of persons to be appointed by the contracting authority.
The multi-eyes principle is designed to prevent individuals from being able to manipulate the offers unchecked when opening the offers.
Bidders will be able to take part in the opening ceremony for most of the bidding procedures.
Only offers that have been submitted to the negotiator at the opening of the first offer are allowed to open.
In principle, late offers may no longer be taken into account.
In order to ensure the transparency of the opening date, the actions taken and the results of the opening of the offer must be recorded in a protocol in which, among other things, the names of the bidders and the offer prices must be recorded.
The protocol must be read out and signed by the negotiating committee.
It can also be signed by the bidders present.
Divergent rules
In the Czech Republic, a committee is carrying out the opening of the bids.
Freelancers can also play a part in this.
The committee can also be tasked with further phases of the award process, such as the evaluation of the offers.
In Germany, a negotiator and a secretary are carrying out the opening of the offer.
The chief negotiator must be an employee of the contracting body.
The chief negotiator and, in the case of contracts in the building, also the writer should not be involved in the processing of the procurement documents, as well as in the award and contract processing.
According to the German regulations, the minutes of the opening date also contain information on discounts and discounts, as well as special features - such as damaged or delayed offers - in addition to the offer prices.
In the Czech Republic, in addition to the offer price, only the language of the offer as well as the signature authority of the applicant will be recorded.
The German regulations stipulate that the open offers must be marked in all parts in such a way that subsequent changes and additions are prevented.
The offers are usually marked by perforations with the date of the opening date. They are to be kept secret after the opening date and may only be made available to those directly responsible for the processing.
Czech regulations do not exist.
If only one bid is received in a tender procedure in the Czech Republic, it must not be opened and must be returned unvalued.
There is no such regulation in Germany. If there is only one offer, it must be opened and then evaluated.
