Examination and evaluation of the offers
Examination and evaluation of the offers The client has to examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.
In doing so, he has to determine the offer for the award of the contract, which is best suited to the requirements according to the given award criteria.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption
The EU's guidelines provide for a multi-level procedure:
First of all, the suitability of the bidders has to be determined.
Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
In principle, companies that are legally convicted of fraud, for example, for bribery, must be excluded from participating in the award process.
The offers made by the non-excluded bidders are to be examined in a computational, technical and economic manner and assessed on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. Offers with unusually low prices have to be examined by the client in particular.
The examination and evaluation of the offers is a particularly tamper-prone phase of the award process.
For example, bidders can be unjustifiably excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can be left in competition.
By favouring or discriminating against bidders, the result of the valuation can be unacceptably impaired and thus the determination of the most economically advantageous offer can be prevented.
The contracting authority must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons responsible for the examination and evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure that the procedure and the decisions taken are transparent and verifiable.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
In line with the requirements of the EU, offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.
The requirements for the companies' proof of aptitude to be presented, as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the assessment and their weighting, are laid down in the notices or in the procurement documents and can no longer be changed during the procedure.
Once the bidding has been verified, the eligibility criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the bids.
The rating has to be limited to the award criteria.
The submitted offers must first be formally examined immediately as to whether they are complete and whether, for example, they contain abnormalities that could indicate possible manipulation intentions.
If bidders are excluded from the further examination and evaluation of their offers, they must be informed immediately.
If the valuation of the offers results in an unreasonably low price, the bidder must be given the opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his offer.
The decisions taken during the examination and evaluation of the offers are to be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Divergent rules
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to those directly responsible for processing.
The inspection of the offers as well as the computational examination of the offers can only be carried out by the contracting authority.
It will only have to employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of the further examination and evaluation tasks is not regulated in more detail.
If freelancers are entrusted with the examination and evaluation, they have to treat the offers confidentially.
They are only allowed to make proposals for the decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.
In the Czech Republic, procurement committees are to be set up to examine and evaluate the offers.
The committees draw up evaluation reports with proposals for contracts.
In the end, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the contracts.
If evidence or declarations requested for the submission of the bid in Germany are only incompletely filed, the contracting authority must give the bidders the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the expiration of the deadline, the offer must be excluded from the evaluation.
In the Czech Republic, it is up to the contracting authority to decide whether it will give bidders the opportunity to complete missing evidence or explanations.
If a bidder fails to do so, it must be ruled out.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers are also to be examined.
If, as a result of the price structure of the offer, there are indications that prices for partial services are too low or too high, the bidder must be asked to remove these ambiguities.
If he fails to do so, and if the contracting authority can provide proof of a mixed calculation of prices, this offer must be ruled out.
This is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant changes in the volume of partial services when calculating their offer, which can lead to significant increases in the cost of construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the appropriateness of the prices for partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
In Germany, a surcharge may not be awarded on offers with unreasonably high or low prices.
If one or more offers fall short of the correct price determination of the client or the offer amounts of the other bidders by 10% or more, the bidders have to prove the correct calculation of their offers.
If they are not able to do so, the contracting authority may rule out the offers in question.
In the Czech Republic, the tender can be cancelled after an assessment of profitability if there are only offers that cannot be justified at low prices.
In contrast to German public procurement law, the surcharge cannot be refused in the case of offers with prices substantially higher than the client's calculation for this reason.
If there is a suspicion of anti-competitive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority must immediately report to its technical supervisor at the leading level.
It has to decide what measures to take and whether to inform the Antitrust Authority or the Public Prosecutor's Office.
For example, the technical supervisor must agree to more than 50,000 euros for construction services, if a contract is to be awarded freely, if a contract is not to be awarded on the offer with the lowest price, or if the tender is to be cancelled.
There are no such regulations in the Czech Republic.
Key findings of the audit
BRH
Suitability and evaluation criteria
The vast majority of the procurement procedures examined were in line with the requirements set out above.
In the case of some companies proposed by freelancers, the contracting authorities did not check the suitability of the companies themselves.
A beneficiary commissioned companies without the required proof of fitness being fully available.
In some cases, it was not clear whether the contracting authority had taken into account all the award criteria announced in its selection decision, or whether it had merely based its award decision on the "price" criterion.
Selection of the people involved and confidentiality of the offers
Some contracting authorities used unauthorised persons to examine the offers for this purpose.
For example, freelance workers or staff involved in planning or carrying out a construction project carried out tasks that could only be carried out by employees of the contracting authority.
The construction services justified this with insufficient staffing capacity in the respective areas.
In some cases, the freelancers charged with examining the offers also worked with employees who were not obliged to keep the offers secret and to comply with the contractual obligations in a conscientious manner.
For the construction services, it was mostly not clear whether the offers for freelancers were only accessible to those directly responsible for processing.
Review and computational examination of the offers
Some contracting authorities handed over the open offers to freelancers for further examination, without first having carried out the prescribed review of the offers and the computational examination itself, and having doctored their results.
In the case of manipulative intentions, third parties would have been able to make changes to the offers without this being understandable to the contracting authorities.
In the documents examined, abnormalities or lack of price or product information were in some cases not marked, or only insufficiently marked.
Performance examinations
In the case of a sample in a civil engineering administration, the cheapest offers for three quarters of the audited procurement procedures deviated more than 10% from the previously determined estimated costs.
One in 20 bidding procedures has been cancelled due to inappropriate bid prices.
Not all of the bidding tests and enlightenment discussions with the bidders were comprehensible or sufficiently documented.
In many cases, there was a lack of more detailed information, such as on the unit prices of the most important positions.
In many cases, the deviations were only generally justified, for example by references to changed market prices or increased material costs.
Construction officials said it was difficult to detect and prove mixed calculations.
In the case of a call for tenders from an institution under public law, the offer price of the cheapest offer was 66% below the previously estimated value of these services.
Further calculations or examinations of the causes of this deviation were not documented.
In an enlightenment interview, the contracting authority found no evidence of price dumping by the then commissioned company.
As a result, it remained unclear whether the estimated value was too high or whether the offer price was too low.
Later, the client assessed the contracted company as a "low-cost company," which could not maintain quality or deadlines.
In another call for tenders, a construction service awarded the contract for an offer, the price of which was 35% higher than the value of the cost assessment.
She did not cancel the call for tenders, citing the non-factual justification that this company could be concluded on a reasonable calculation.
Suspicions of irregularities
There have been two cases of irregularities in an audited building administration, both of which have been reported to the technical supervisor.
In one of the cases, the calculation of two bidders was identical in a call for tenders, so that the contracting authority excluded both bids from the procedure.
In the application of the remaining regulations, the tests did not give rise to any significant objections.
