Aptitude test
For many of the construction projects examined, including university construction, road construction and the extension of the rail network, the contracting authorities did not exclude bidders from the procedure, although they did not meet the requirements set out in the tender documents or could not prove their suitability to the prescribed extent. On the other hand, in one case, a contracting authority could neither prove nor explain why it had excluded a bidder who had met the requirements.
Scoring
When awarding construction services for a water treatment plant, the contracting authority did not take into account the specified evaluation criteria when examining and evaluating the offers.
In the case of a construction project to expand the railway network, the contracting authority only determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road conservation measures, the predetermined criterion of "shortening the construction phase" was misjudged in a procedure.
As a result, the proposed reduction was insufficiently taken into account by bidders in second and third positions.
Documentation of the selection of offers
In three procurement procedures in the context of housing development, the contracting authority did not document the criteria it applied and the basis on which it had selected the successful bidder.
During the construction of a motorway, the contracting authority selected companies for smaller orders of up to 20,000 euros on the basis of telephone surveys on prices and delivery conditions alone.
Examinations of this selection were not possible, as the interviews were not documented.
Summary findings
The regulations for testing and evaluating the offers in both countries are in line with the requirements of the EU.
However, with regard to the details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective regulations differ from each other.
In Germany, the process is more regulated than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multi-eyes principle and for the protection of offers.
The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the appropriateness of the prices offered must be assessed.
In both countries, in some of the procurement procedures examined, it had to be established that significant procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of the offers were not, or were not, sufficiently documented.
However, without traceability and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, possible manipulative interventions will be encouraged.
A particularly serious defect was the handing over of all offers to third parties, without the public contracting authority having sufficiently examined and documented the offers beforehand, thereby protecting them from possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
If public authorities have tasks carried out by third parties in the examination and evaluation of the offers, sufficient precautions and an increased control effort are required to counter the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the adequacy of the prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the specified instruments, and did not sufficiently examine the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, complaints arose mainly during the aptitude test as well as in the application of the evaluation criteria.
Completion of the award procedure
After testing and valuing the bids, the award process will be completed by awarding the contract or by cancelling the procedure.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
The companies have the possibility to examine the intended award in the case of information by electronic means or by fax within 10 days or with other means of communication within 15 days and, if necessary, to initiate a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the end of this information period.
