If a bidder makes a request for a review within the information period, it is only possible to conclude a contract after the final decision in the review procedure.
Companies can also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court as part of this review process.
The review procedure is intended to ensure the legal protection of the companies and to encourage the client to comply with the public procurement law throughout the award procedure.
In order to do this, he has to document the procedure sufficiently.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the contracting authority has to decide on the award of the contract.
However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of a proper examination and evaluation of the offers.
The client is to issue the order within the announced deadline for the award of the contract,
This is also because the bidders are no longer bound by their offers after the deadline.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and limited tenders, the client must not, in principle, deviate from the content of the offer at the time of conclusion of the contract.
The inferior bidders must be informed of the award decision and the reasons for not taking their offers into account in a timely manner.
Tendering procedures may only be cancelled under certain conditions, for example if the offer prices are excessive or if the offers do not meet the requirements of the tender.
Divergent rules
In the Czech Republic, the 10-day or 15-day obligation to provide information and maintenance prior to the award of the contract also applies to construction services that are not to be awarded across Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to the area of EU-wide distribution.
In the case of other proceedings in Germany, bidders can only be informed of the award decision after the award of the contract.
In the Czech Republic, an award procedure has to be repealed if only one offer has been received or only one offer has been evaluated.
In Germany, the surcharge must also be awarded in the case of only one valuable offer, provided that it meets the conditions of the tender and is economical.
Key findings of the audit
BRH
In the case of verified contracts, there were only a few complaints at the conclusion of the award procedures.
In some cases, companies have already received letters of order for EU-wide contracts before the end of the information deadlines, which may result in the ineffectiveness of the contract.
According to open procedures, contract letters also contained content that deviated from the content of the offer in individual cases, such as changed dates.
In several cases, the contracting authorities did not comply with the award deadlines.
In the case of an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the contract for the second cheapest offer, as a company with a 50% cheaper offer was no longer prepared to carry out the services at the price originally offered after the expiration of the contract period.
