In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content in the contract.
In the case of some contracts, such as road maintenance works, the construction of a motorway and a bypass, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts at the end of the legal period.
When awarding construction services for the refurbishment of former military sites, the contracting authority only directed the announcement of the award of the contract to all bidders after the expiry of the legal deadline.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements at the end of the procurement process.
The legal protection of the inferior candidates or bidders will increase the instruments for preventing corruption.
In Czech public procurement law, the scope of legal protection is also extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.
In both countries, the deadlines for awarding contracts have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
In the future, building authorities should avoid the shortcomings that have been identified in the completion of their procurement procedures.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The award procedures are to be documented clearly during their individual stages in view of the relevant findings as well as the reasons for the individual decisions.
In the case of EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made known.
The order data will also be recorded in an EU statistic.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption Through the documentation of the procurement procedures, a basic requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement is implemented.
A carefully and promptly prepared documentation makes it possible to trace the award decisions.
In particular, it also provides effective legal protection for bidders for contracts above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to substantiate procurement decisions in detail significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.
The notice of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure has to be sent to the EU Office for Official Publications within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, which also implements the transparency requirement.
The contracting authorities also have to collect the essential data from their procurement procedures and report it to the EU Commission via the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the EU Commission draws up annual EU statistics to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully implemented the EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Divergent rules
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not only limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.
The notice period is shortened to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide contracts, there is an obligation to publish only in the case of limited tenders and in the case of free-to-air contracts from value limits of 25,000 euros and 15,000 euros without VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits, as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure will receive information about the orders.
