Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits carried out by the NIC and the BRH have focused on two main areas, which are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of construction services by public authorities: The application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law allow cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only designed to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two audit courts on the application of the public procurement rules in both countries, as well as the comparison of these regulations, provide insights into the similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their public procurement law and its application.
Application of EU public procurement rules
Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements for the award of construction services into national law.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and in Germany, there is an important common basis for awarding construction services and for taking into account the essential requirements of competition, the equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of the procurement procedures.
The building authorities in both countries have, in some cases, largely backed up these bids with additional administrative provisions.
The Czech Republic has also largely transferred the requirements for the construction services to be awarded across the EU to its nationally adjustable procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, investigations carried out by the audit bodies have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The building authorities in Germany should further improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to be able to remove the complaints that have been raised in the implementation of the EU requirements.
In particular, the tests carried out in the Czech Republic have highlighted risks that affect the cost-effectiveness of the contracts.
For example, incomplete performance descriptions required additional services, which were often awarded in violation of legislation. In addition, cost surveys were mostly insufficiently prepared, and excessive qualification requirements reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the transport sector.
Prevention of corruption
The investigations have not been aimed at exposing cases of corruption,
This is also because the courts of auditors do not have the appropriate instruments to do so.
However, the audit courts can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the awarding of construction services and how these requirements are applied.
When it comes to preventing corruption, both countries have set different priorities.
In particular, the German regulations provide for largely unlimited competition, as well as transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of the procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of the prevention of corruption apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared to their specific requirements.
In some cases, the relevant regulations set out very precisely how the anti-corruption bids should be taken into account in the course of the award process and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the opinion of the BRH, in particular, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender is a suitable instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of construction services. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.
Risk analysis and sufficient controls (in particular the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures, as well as various organisational measures, are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The BRH therefore does not see any fundamental need for changes to the corresponding requirements of the administrations for the award of construction services.
The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some of the requirements.
The building authorities should continue to train their employees on the requirements for the prevention of corruption and make them even more aware of this problem.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building authorities had delegated to freelancers.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.
Manipulation and corruption-prone tasks should therefore only be assigned to third parties if the administration is able to guarantee a sufficient level of protection against undue interference.
