The Czech Republic has adopted an anti-corruption strategy at government level, in which the area of public procurement is the most important element.
The Procurement Act, as well as its implementing provisions, have been substantially amended.
The tests carried out by the NK were carried out during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures, since the contracting authorities must justify the cost-effectiveness of the orders, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential assessment criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and must properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The NAC and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU guidelines.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideal potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both audit bodies consider that the building authorities in their countries are required to continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks, in order to be able to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures can provide a wider scope for competition and significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
In addition, a greater division of construction services into lots can have a favourable effect on the offer price, provided that it achieves greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring that procurement procedures are carried out correctly is an essential basis for efficient awarding of contracts by public authorities.
In Germany, procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised construction authorities, while in the Czech Republic, these tasks - with the exception of transport construction projects - are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.
The audit courts of both countries have the concern to continue to develop the relevant findings for them, even after the completion of their joint project, and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.
Both audit bodies are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
